s of anti-Semitism are notably higher among black Americans than among white Americans, they demonstrate that taking pride in being black does not encourage blacks to be more suspicious or intolerant of others who are not black. The higher levels of anti-Semitism are instead associated with a gallery of oversimplified and accusatory ideas, including a popularized Afrocentrism and charges of vast conspiracies, that have won substantial support in the black community. Readers of this book will come away with an understanding of how African Americans, while insistent on winning racial justice, are deeply committed to the values of the American ethos and their identity as Americans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxAttitudes. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aPrejudiceszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aAdler, Marc.  aAfrocentricity.  aAnti-Defamation League.  aAristotle.  aBerlin, Isaiah.  aBlack Panther Movement.  aBobo, Lawrence.  aChurchill, Winston.  aCokely, Steve.  aCombs, Michael.  aConverse, Philip.  aDavis, Darren.  aDawson, Michael C.  aEqual Opportunity experiment.  aGarvey, Marcus.  aGilens, Martin.  aGlazer, Nathan.  aHerring, Mary.  aHofstadter, Richard.  aHutchings, Vincent.  aIndex of Conspiratorial Thinking.  aJackson, Jesse.  aJankowski, Thomas B.  aJeffries, Leonard.  aKarenga, Ron.  aKennedy, John F.  aLepkowski, James M.  aMarable, Manning.  aMcWhorter, John.  aMuhammad, Elijah.  aMuhammed, Khalid.  aNewton, Huey.  aOswald, Lee Harvey.  aRedistricting experiment.  aReed, Adolph.  aSawyer, Eugene.  aSelznick, Gertrude.  aSigelman, Lee.  aSteinberg, Stephen.  aTate, Katherine.  aTaylor, Charles.  aTurner, Patricia.  aWelch, Susan.  aWest, Cornell